      <file>.claude/patterns/api/send-email-integration.md</file>
    </files>
  </knowledge>

  <steps>
    <step order="1">List the 9 files in `src/solutions/LegalWorkspace/src/components/SummarizeFiles/`. Verify count matches empirical pre-flight (CLAUDE.md row 9 implies "9 files"). If count diverges, document the delta and proceed with whatever is there.</step>
    <step order="2">Grep audit consumers BEFORE deletion. Find every file in `src/solutions/LegalWorkspace/` that imports from the fork:
      <code>
      grep -rn 'from .*components/SummarizeFiles' src/solutions/LegalWorkspace/
      grep -rn 'from .*SummarizeFiles/SummarizeSendEmailStep\|from .*SummarizeFiles/SummarizeFilesDialog' src/solutions/LegalWorkspace/
      grep -rn 'import.*SummarizeFiles' src/solutions/LegalWorkspace/
      </code>
      Produce a deduplicated list of consumer files. Note: every consumer becomes task 062's retarget candidate.
    </step>
    <step order="3">Inspect each consumer briefly to understand: what symbol is being imported? (`SummarizeFilesDialog`, `SummarizeSendEmailStep`, both, or a transitive sub-component?) Record in audit list.</step>
    <step order="4">Append the audit list to `current-task.md` with a section heading `## Wave 4 SummarizeFiles fork consumers (for task 062 retarget)` — format as a checklist task 062 ticks off.</step>
    <step order="5">Delete the directory with `git rm -r src/solutions/LegalWorkspace/src/components/SummarizeFiles/` (or equivalent). Confirm: directory gone, 9 files removed from git tracking.</step>
    <step order="6">DO NOT attempt to build LegalWorkspace from this task — build break is expected. Document the expected break in task notes.</step>
    <step order="7">Update `projects/email-communication-solution-r3/tasks/TASK-INDEX.md`: mark task 061 ✅ completed.</step>
    <step order="8">Update `projects/email-communication-solution-r3/current-task.md` per task-execute protocol: status → completed, advance to next pending task (062 — which immediately repairs the break).</step>
  </steps>

  <tools>
    <tool name="bash">List files + run `git rm -r`</tool>
    <tool name="grep">Consumer audit before deletion</tool>
    <tool name="edit">Update current-task.md with consumer audit list</tool>
  </tools>

  <outputs>
    <output type="delete">src/solutions/LegalWorkspace/src/components/SummarizeFiles/ (DELETED — 9 files)</output>
    <output type="notes">current-task.md (UPDATED — consumer audit list for task 062)</output>
  </outputs>

  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion testable="true">`src/solutions/LegalWorkspace/src/components/SummarizeFiles/` directory does not exist.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">`git status` shows 9 files staged for deletion.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Consumer audit list (every LegalWorkspace file that imported from the deleted directory) appended to `current-task.md`.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Task notes document the expected build break + handoff to task 062.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">`TASK-INDEX.md` marks task 061 ✅ completed.</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>

  <notes>
    Expected build break: LegalWorkspace will not compile between this task and task 062. This is intentional and documented. The temporary break window MUST be short (sequential tasks 061 → 062 in same session). Do NOT merge a PR that contains only 061 — task 062 must land in the same PR or sequentially without merge intervening.

    File count delta: if the actual file count is not 9, that does not block this task — record the actual count in notes. The 9-file count from CLAUDE.md is empirical pre-flight; pre-existing file changes between pre-flight and execution may have shifted it.

    Reversibility: this entire task is reversible via `git revert`. The file deletion is the only physical state change — the audit list lives in `current-task.md` and survives revert.

    If a consumer in step 2's audit is found to reference a symbol that LegalWorkspace adds on top of the shared lib's component (i.e., LegalWorkspace had legitimate value-add code, not just a copy), document it in task notes and escalate to project owner. The default assumption is the fork is pure duplication.
  </notes>

